answers.body_markdown:
It&#39;s because when you&#39;re including just the reducer, your state is a simple object like so:
```
state {
  isOpen: [],
  ....
}
```

When you `combineReducers`, you pass in an object with the following structure:
```
{ stateKey1: reducer, stateKey2: reducer2...etc }
```
`stateKey1` and `stateKey2` are actually substates of your redux apps, which help drive down complexity and keep your components as individual as possible.

in your case, this means that your reducer state will actually be nested one level down, which means your state will now look like:
```
state {
  reducer {
    isOpen: []
    ...
  }
}
```
where, `&#39;reducer&#39;` is the key you give to the object passed as argument to `combineReducers`;
To fix this, wherever you are consuming the redux state as props, access them like so:

```
const mapStateToProps = state =&gt; ({isOpen: state.reducer.isOpen});
```

